Introduction

For this assignment youâll be making a few charts and maps using the ggplot2 and tmap packages we discussed in the last class session.

To help in your efforts, do feel free to make use of and adapt the materials we went over in class, which are located here.

The data used for this assignment includes Georgia election results by county for U.S. Senate and Governor in 2022, President in 2020, and then some of the same socioeconomic factors weâve looked at other contexts so far during the semester.

Loading the Data

The first step is to load in the data, which is stored in the ga_votes.xlsx Excel file thatâs included in this repository. As youâll see if you open the spreadsheet itself, there are two tabs - one contains the senate results, and one contains the governor results.

Weâll load them separately into two datasets to be used for the remainder of this assignment.

#import the GA election data for this assignment

#GA senate
senate_results <- read_excel(here("ga_votes.xlsx"), sheet = "senate")

#GA governor
governor_results <- read_excel(here("ga_votes.xlsx"), sheet = "governor")

Two columns in particular to highlight that weâll use to examine how the Republican Senate and Governor candidates did compared with former President Trumpâs performance in 2020:

  • pct_r_above_trump. This column calculates the difference in percentage points between what the 2022 Republican candidate got (pct_r_2022) and what Trump got two years earlier (pct_r_2020). A negative value means the candidate did worse than Trump, a positive value means they did better.

  • is_r_above_trump. This companion columns is a so-called âflagâ column, which provides a Yes/No as to whether the Republican candidate did better or worse than Trump. In other words, is the pct_r_above_trump value positive or negative.

Charts

For this section use the ggplot2 package to create your charts.

1)

For the Senate race, create a column/bar chart that shows how many counties the Republican candidate did better vs.Â worse than Trump.

senate_results = senate_results %>%
  mutate(
    is_r_above_trump_new = ifelse(is_r_above_trump=="Y", "Better", "Worse")
  )

ggplot(senate_results, aes(x = is_r_above_trump_new)) + 
  geom_bar(fill = "#9ebcda") +
  xlab("Performance") +
  ylab("Number of counties") +
  labs(title = "Republican senate candidate performance compared to Trump in GA counties") +
  theme_clean()

3)

For the Senate race, create a chart that shows the top 10 biggest drops between the Republican candidate and Trump (i.e.Â the 10 counties with the most substantial negative numbers in pct_r_above_trump). Remember that you can slice off a certain number of rows using the head() function, i.e.Â head(5), head(20), etc.

Your chart should be sorted from the biggest drop to the smallest among the top 10 counties.

senate_drops = senate_results %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  summarize(pct_r_above_trump = pct_r_above_trump) %>%
  arrange(pct_r_above_trump) %>%
  head(10)

senate_drops %>%
  arrange(pct_r_above_trump) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(county, desc(pct_r_above_trump)), y = pct_r_above_trump)) + 
  geom_col(fill = "#9ebcda") +
  coord_flip() + 
  xlab("Counties") +
  ylab("Percentage") +
  labs(title = "Highest drops between Republican candidates and Trump in GA counties (Top 10)") +
  theme_clean()

4)

For the Senate race, create a chart that shows the top 10 counties highest margins of victory for the Democratic candidate. To do that youâll need to compare the Democratic candidateâs percentage (pct_d_2022) with the Republicanâs (pct_r_2022) to calculate the margin of victory for each county.

senate_results = senate_results %>%
  mutate(
    d_margin = pct_d_2022 - pct_r_2022
  )

dem_margin_s = senate_results %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  summarize(d_margin = d_margin) %>%
  arrange(desc(d_margin)) %>%
  head(10)

dem_margin_s %>%
  arrange(desc(d_margin)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(county, d_margin), y = d_margin)) + 
  geom_col(fill = "#9ebcda") +
  coord_flip() + 
  xlab("Counties") +
  ylab("Democratic margin of victory percentage") +
  labs(title = "Highest Democratic margins of victory for senate race in GA counties (Top 10)",
       subtitle = "2022") +
  theme_clean()

Now do the same as Question 4, only this time for the race for Governor instead.

governor_results = governor_results %>%

    d_margin = pct_d_2022 - pct_r_2022

dem_margin_g = governor_results %>%

6)

Extra credit: determine the top 10 counties with the biggest differences between what the Republican candidate for Governor received and what the Senate candidate received.

(Note that to accomplish this youâll have to first run a join that merges the two datasets, so that you have both the senate and governor version of the pct_r_2022 column in the same table.)

# .x are senate results; .y are governor results
sen_gov_results = inner_join(senate_results, governor_results, by=c("county"="county"))

sen_gov_results = sen_gov_results %>% 
  mutate(pct_r_diff = pct_r_2022.y - pct_r_2022.x)

r_diff = sen_gov_results %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  summarize(pct_r_diff = pct_r_diff) %>%
  arrange(desc(pct_r_diff)) %>%
  head(10)

r_diff %>%
  arrange(desc(pct_r_diff)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(county, pct_r_diff), y = pct_r_diff)) + 
  geom_col(fill = "#9ebcda") +
  coord_flip() + 
  xlab("Counties") +
  ylab("Percent difference") +
  labs(title = "Pct differences between Republican senate and governor candidates in GA counties (Top 10)",
       subtitle = "2022") +
  theme_clean()

7)

For the Senate race, create a choropleth (shaded) map of Georgia counties that shows where the Republican candidate for Senate did better vs.Â worse than Trump.

new_senate_sf = counties_geo %>%
  left_join(. , senate_results, by=c("NAME"="county"))

tm_shape(new_senate_sf) + 
  tm_fill(col="pct_r_above_trump", title = "Percent difference from Trump") + 
  tm_layout(main.title = "Republican senate candidate performance compared to Trump in GA counties",
            main.title.size = 0.7,
            legend.outside = TRUE,
            legend.outside.size = 0.5,
            legend.text.size = 1) + 
  tm_polygons()
